    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my ac unit outside is acting weird. the fan is making this constant humming sound but the blades arent actually spinning. i can hear the motor trying to work but nothing is moving. what is probably wrong with it and what should i do before i try to look at it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A humming motor without spinning blades is a classic symptom of a faulty capacitor, a common issue in AC units, especially those with older designs. It's like a mischievous little goblin trying to trick you into thinking the motor is working, but really, it's just a clever ruse. \n\nBefore you start tinkering, make sure to unplug the unit from the power source to avoid any accidental shocks or electrical surprises. You don't want to get zapped by a rogue electrical current, trust me, it's not worth the risk. \n\nOnce you've safely disconnected the power, take a closer look at the capacitor, which is usually located near the motor. If it's blown, you'll see signs of physical damage or a blown fuse. If it's not blown, try checking the capacitor's voltage rating and ensure it's compatible with the unit's specifications. A mismatched capacitor can be a real pain to deal with, but it's not as bad as trying to fix a faulty capacitor in a unit that's been clogged with gunk and grime, if you know what I mean. \n\nIf you're not comfortable with DIY repairs or if the issue persists after checking the capacitor, it's best to call a",
