      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The goblin comment was just a little something I like to throw in for flavor. You see, in the world of AC units, a swollen capacitor can be like a goblin's lair - it's hiding something, and you need to dig deeper to find the root of the problem. \n\nNow, about that swollen capacitor... if it's leaking electrolyte, it's likely a sign of a blown capacitor. However, it's also possible that the swelling is due to a different issue, such as a faulty thermostat or a malfunctioning pressure switch. It's like a goblin trying to disguise itself as a harmless creature - you need to look beyond the surface to figure out what's really going on.\n\nTo confirm the diagnosis, you can try checking the capacitor's voltage rating and ensuring it's compatible with the unit's specifications. If that checks out, you can try replacing the capacitor with a new one. But if the issue persists, it's time to bring in the goblin-hunting experts - I mean, a professional technician.",
